INTERVIEW_FETCH = '<content>\n# Practice Guides\n1. Legend:\n\\t<table>\n\\t<colgroup>\n\\t<col width="106.4609375">\n\\t<col width="106.4765625">\n\\t</colgroup>\n<tr>\n<td>Style</td>\n<td>Meaning</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span color="pink_bg">pink highlight</span></td>\n<td>from Michelle</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span color="blue_bg">blue highlight</span></td>\n<td>from Jane</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span underline="true">underlined</span></td>\n<td>practiced</td>\n</tr>\n\\t</table>\n2. Everyone has to add **3 general questions** and **1 random question** **every week**.\n3. Everyone is free to add answers under:\n\\t1. **general questions** <span underline="true">at any time</span>\n\\t2. **random question** <span underline="true">after it is practiced</span>\n4. Practice Schedule: every Tuesday & Thursday 8-10 sgt (for September)\n5. Practice flow:\n\\t<table>\n\\t<colgroup>\n\\t<col width="37.3671875">\n\\t<col width="374.3125">\n\\t<col width="171.66666666666666">\n\\t</colgroup>\n<tr>\n<td>No</td>\n<td>Activity</td>\n<td>Duration</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>Practice last week\'s questions without reading answers</td>\n<td>20 mins</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2. </td>\n<td>Practice this week\'s questions with reading answers</td>\n<td>20 mins</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3.</td>\n<td>Give comments</td>\n<td>20 mins</td>\n</tr>\n\\t</table>\n# General Questions\n1. <span color="pink_bg">Introduce yourself</span>\n\\t**Michelle\'s answer**:\n\\tMy name is Michelle, I am currently a <span underline="true">third year student in UOW</span>, majoring in <span underline="true">Computer Science (Big Data and Cyber Security)</span>. I love coding, playing puzzle games, playing few musical instruments like electone, guzheng, and ocarina, and I often dance too.\n\\t**Jane\'s answer**:\n\\tHello, My name is Jingen, you can also call me my english name, Jane. I am a student who currently study big data and cyber security in university of wollongong. I have four months internship about back-end development. I love coding and outdoor activities like hiking.\n2. <span color="pink_bg">What is your biggest achievement?</span>\n\\t**Michelle\'s answer**:\n\\tOne of my biggest achievements was during one of the hackathons I went a few months ago. We had less than 24 hours to build a recipe app, and my team has a lot of ideas to build: recipe app using <span underline="true">computer vision, voice recognition, text-to-speech, using AI to change recipe for diet and allergy, and also answering user when they encounter any problem in cooking process</span>. That was a lot to take on but none of us had really worked with all those features before, so we had to learn, apply, and debug everything on the spot. I was so locked in that I <span underline="true">did not really take breaks</span> (except when I go to toilet), and even when I ate I kept thinking about what to fix next. It was exhausting since I only <span underline="true">slept for about 15 minutes</span>, but it was also one of the most fun hackathon experience I\'ve ever had. <span underline="true">What I am most proud of is not just that we got the app working, but the fact that we still managed to do what we thought was impossible</span>. It made me believe that as long as we stay focused, keep learning, and support each other, even the things that look impossible can actually be done.\n\\t(If the interviewer ask abt the project)\n\\tSo we added a feature where user can just use hand gesture to tell the app to go to next or previous page instead of clicking the screen in case our hands are dirty. There\'s also AI that can guide user through each steps and can even think of the possible solution to mistakes that user made during the cooking process and modify the steps user needs to do next. It can also modify the recipe based on user\'s diet restriction like vegan or lactose intolerant. There were a lot of features that we planned to make and in the end we still manage to finish all of them. Even though we did not win the first place, but it was a very fun experience and it really boosts my confidence and made me believe that even if it seems impossible, as long as we\'re willing to try, we will definitely learn a lot of new things.\n\\t**Jane\'s answer**:\n\\tMy greatest achievement was inventing a data cleaning tool during my internship. Compared to previous tools, this tool has two more generation boxes - cor_log and lab_log, which are used to compare the important information captured by the AI before and after the modification. Combined with human judgment and modification, it greatly improves data accuracy and makes manual review more convenient. Staff can judge the correct information from the case without having to repeatedly review the case, which improves work efficiency and reduces labor costs.\n3. <span color="pink_bg">What is your biggest strength and weakness?</span>\n\\t**Michelle\'s answer**:\n\\tMy biggest strength is that I <span underline="true">love learning something new</span> and I\'m also a <span underline="true">fast learner</span>. That\'s why I love to <span underline="true">do different kind of project and join a lot of hackathons</span>, as they are the fastest way for me to learn a lot of new knowledge and skills by practice and even observing how other people work too. While my biggest weakness is my <span underline="true">public speaking skill</span>, I was a very shy person so I used to only listen to other people but hesitated to add my opinion too. But ever since I joined uni, I started to push myself out of my comfort zone and started small from <span underline="true">being a workshop leader into taking leadership roles</span> in CCAs in my university. I am still not really good in public speaking, but <span underline="true">I think I have improved a lot compared to my previous self and will still continue to learn and improve</span>.\n\\t**Jane\'s answer**:\n\\tMy biggest strength is that I\'m very <span underline="true">willing to learn things</span> I\'m not good at and I\'m not afraid of <span underline="true">trying new challenges</span>. I\'m also a bit of a perfectionist, which means I like to make sure my work is accurate and <span underline="true">high-quality</span>.\n\\tAs for my weakness, I can be a <span underline="true">little shy and not the most outgoing</span> person, so I sometimes prefer to stay by myself rather than talk to others. But I\'ve been <span underline="true">pushing myself to improve</span> this by <span underline="true">joining group projects and student activities</span>, which helps me get more comfortable communicating and working with different people\n4. <span color="red_bg">How do you describe yourself in 3 words? And why?</span>\n\\t**Michelle**:\n\\tI would describe myself as curious, dedicated, and a peacemaker. I am curious because I am always eager to learn something new and open to exploring different perspectives. I am dedicated because I value every opportunity I am given, so I put my best effort into whatever I am doing. As for peacemaker, I value harmony the most in a team, but I also understand that healthy conflict is sometimes necessary, so I try to maintain it by understanding my teammates and resolve conflicts so that we can work well together.\n\\t**Jane**:\n\\tI would describe myself as curious, resilient, and detail-oriented. Curious because I enjoy learning new tools and concepts outside my comfort zone, which helps me adapt quickly. Resilient because even when I face difficulties, I don\'t give up and keep trying until I find a solution. And detail-oriented because I always check my work carefully to make sure it is accurate and reliable\n5. <span color="red_bg">How do you usually handle conflict between peers in a project?</span>\n\\t**Michelle**:<br>When there\'s conflict, I usually start by <span underline="true">listening</span> to both sides and trying to <span underline="true">understand what they really need</span>. For example, once <span underline="true">a teammate felt another wasn\'t doing enough</span> because she was traveling, and <span underline="true">he confronted her a bit too directly</span>. She felt it was unfair since she had already told the team about her travel. I spoke to them separately, I reassured the traveling teammate and <span underline="true">explained that the message could have been delivered in a more respectful way</span>, and I also suggested her to share more details in advance about when she would be back and available. To the other teammate, I suggested we could <span underline="true">balance things by giving her more tasks after her trip</span>. After that, both sides felt understood, and we were able to <span underline="true">move forward without tension</span> and continue working well together\n\\t**Jane**: \n\\tWhen conflict happens in a project team, I first try to listen to both sides to understand the root cause. I stay calm and avoid taking sides, because I believe most disagreements come from miscommunication or different priorities. Then I encourage open discussion, focusing on the project goals rather than personal differences. If needed, I suggest compromises or clarify responsibilities so everyone feels heard and we can move forward productively\n6. <span color="red_bg">What was the biggest challenge you have faced and how did you solve it?</span>\n\\t**Michelle**:\n\\tThe biggest challenge I have ever faced was during my <span underline="true">first hackathon</span>, when I accidentally joined a <span underline="true">Web3 hackathon</span>. At first <span underline="true">I did not realize how difficult Web3 was</span>, but soon I found out it was a very advanced topic and definitely not beginner-friendly. Despite that, I was determined to keep learning and contributing. The <span underline="true">biggest challenge was the lack of information, even ChatGPT could not help much at that time because of that</span>. So I looked for other ways, like <span underline="true">watching YouTube tutorials and even reading other people\'s code on GitHub</span>. And it felt like a <span underline="true">treasure hunt</span>, where we treat every single useful link or document like a treasure we found and shared to learn together. It made me realize that even if I don\'t feel fully prepared, <span underline="true">as long as I keep trying and look for creative ways to learn, I can still move forward and figure things out</span>.\n\\t**Jane**: \n\\tThe biggest challenge I faced was overcoming my fear of coding errors. In the beginning, I was very afraid of seeing red error lines on the screen, and I didn\'t really know how to solve them. I realized that if I didn\'t deal with this fear, it would always limit me in my studies and future work.\n\\tTo overcome this, I decided to face the problem directly. I started by watching YouTube tutorials and taking free online courses to strengthen my coding basics. Whenever I didn\'t understand something, I would try again and again until it clicked. I also asked AI tools and friends for help, and I pushed myself to practice more by doing small freelance projects.\n\\tAs a result, I made big progress. I\'m no longer afraid of errors, because I see them as part of the learning process. Now I can build simple projects independently, and I feel much more confident in my coding skills.\n7. <span color="pink_bg">What\'s your most significant leadership experience?</span>\n\\t**Michelle**:\n\\t**Jane**:\n8. <span color="pink_bg">What are your future goals?</span>\n\\t**Michelle**:\n\\t**Jane**:\n9. <span color="pink_bg">How do you handle stress?</span>\n\\t**Michelle**:\n\\t**Jane**:\n# Random Questions\n1. <span color="pink_bg">If you are an animal, what kind of animal are you and why?</span>\n\\t**Michelle\'s answer**: Dove, peacemaker\n\\t**Jane\'s answer**: Dog, extrovert\n2. <span color="pink_bg">If you\'re given a million dollar, how would you spend it?</span>\n\\t**Michelle**: half invest or save for startup, some for family, few for donation, the rest savings\n\\t**Jane**: half to bank, half to buy house, car, travel around the world\n3. <span color="pink_bg">If you were a crayon, what color would you be and why?</span>\n\\t**Michelle**: \n\\t**Jane**: \n# Comments\n## 16 September 2025\n### Michelle\'s Comment:\n-Don\'t "ck" too much, preferably just be silent while thinking. You can ask tell interviewer for some time to think like "Sorry may I have a moment to think about this?"\n+Explained cor_log and lab_log really well even though it\'s not in the script. You are capable of explaining the things you understand really well, so just be confident about it :D.\n### Jane\'s Comment:\n-Second question can shorten a little bit, achievement looks like there are some bugs and could be improved a bit\n+very fluently for every questions, very confident, jiayou jiayou\n## 1 October 2025\n### Michelle\'s Comment:\n-experiment → experience\n-some "uh"s\n-resilience → resilient\n+quite fluent for question 3\n+no more "ck"\n+question 5 very good, i like it\n### Jane\'s Comment:\n-question 5 example too long \n+talking very naturally\n</content>'

